The Briefing  By Martin Peers SUPPORTED BY TITAN February 24, 2022 Greetings!  It didn’t take long today for U.S. investors to shrug off worries about Russia’s attack on Ukraine. After an initial broad market sell-off, tech stocks rallied strongly this afternoon, lifting the Nasdaq index by 3.3%. That might seem a surprising reaction given the potentially catastrophic effects of a European war on the global economy. Then again, this is the same stock market that two years ago ignored the threat of a global pandemic almost until lockdowns were implemented in the U.S. Don’t read anything into one day’s movements in stock prices.  We’re not going to pretend to have any idea how this conflict will evolve and what the impact will be for U.S. businesses and the tech sector. But there are sure to be some ripple effects. This Bloomberg report smartly pointed out that global supply problems, which have caused havoc for the e-commerce and advertising-related sectors, could get worse. The chip industry, already struggling with shortages, could be further squeezed, Reuters reported. Meanwhile, higher oil prices will feed inflation, which will only heighten the need for higher interest rates. (See our report here on tech firms evacuating workers from Ukraine).  As far as specific sectors are concerned, a war in Europe won’t help international travel, already squeezed by the pandemic. Notably, though, Airbnb’s stock ticked up a bit today after dropping nearly 20% over the past few days, suggesting investors think the impact on the company will be limited. Given how well Airbnb has recovered from the early days of the pandemic, that’s an understandable reaction. Meanwhile, given cyberattacks already underway in Ukraine, security firms will be working overtime. What’s less obvious is how the conflict will affect public cloud services like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft’s Azure and Google Cloud.   And while this is a tragedy for the people of Ukraine, the ramifications will be much more frightening if this conflict spreads elsewhere in Europe. This kind of situation can develop in unforeseen ways. After all, two years ago no one expected Covid-19 would still be around today.    Coinbase’s Humdinger of a Quarter  The late-in-the-year crypto selloff certainly didn’t hurt Coinbase, which today reported revenues of $2.5 billion for the fourth quarter, compared to $585 million a year earlier. Free cash flow hit $3 billion, bringing the total cash production for the year 2021 to $10.7 billion—more than triple 2020’s figure. That’s money Coinbase can use for more venture investments and product developments.  Still, a price drop as sharp as the one we’ve seen lately—bitcoin prices are down 45% since early November—will eventually cause a pullback in trading. Coinbase warned it expected overall volume to be lower in the first quarter than it was last quarter. But Coinbase also made clear it has no idea what the full year holds.  The company projected that the number of users trading monthly on the exchange could be anywhere between 5 million and 15 million—compared to an average of 8.4 million for 2021. “It is currently too early to provide a more precise range,” Coinbase explained. Enough said.  Can Zaslav Solve the Streaming Spending Conundrum?  We’re just a few weeks away from Discovery+ owner Discovery completing its combination with HBO Max’s owner WarnerMedia, creating a more potent rival to Netflix and others in streaming. And today, as Discovery reported its fourth-quarter results, CEO David Zaslav signaled he won’t be competing with Netflix to spend the most on programming. In fact, Zaslav made a credible argument that there’s a diminishing return to incremental programming investment.  HBO Max, for instance, currently has a handful of high-profile shows including hits like “Euphoria.” But “would HBO be doing a lot better if it had three more very successful scripted series at the moment? It’s not clear,” Zaslav said on an analyst conference call. Similarly, he noted that Discovery’s Food Network could make its audience “a little bit happier” if it widened its programming selection. But then the Food Network, which is now hugely profitable, “would make no money.”  Zaslav described Discovery as “a real company” that generates billions in cash every year. That was a not-so-subtle swipe at Netflix, which has burned through billions in recent years on a massive programming budget. Netflix’s extravagant spending has undoubtedly helped it sign up more subscribers than anyone else. But even for viewers, its spray-and-pray approach to programming selection isn’t ideal. The service offers so many shows that they can be hard for the audience to sort through. Is there a middle road here? The onus is on Zaslav to find it.   Digital Media Haircuts  It’s not just BuzzFeed’s poor shareholders that have had to take a metaphorical haircut on their digital media investments. Discovery disclosed today that it wrote down its 25% stake in Group Nine Media to reflect the “fair value” implicit in Group Nine’s merger with Vox Media. Discovery’s write-down of $85 million wiped away nearly a third of the value at which it was carrying the stake.   That suggests the Vox deal valued Group Nine at $764 million, well below the billion dollar–plus valuation Group Nine reached after its PopSugar acquisition in 2019. While trumpeting the deal, Vox had not disclosed the valuations implicit in the all-stock merger. So we don’t know whether Vox shareholders also took a haircut. To find that out, we’ll have to wait until Vox goes public—if it ever does.  In Other News…  Insight Partners, a New York–based private investment fund, has raised $20 billion for its 12th fund, far exceeding the previously reported $16 billion target. The new fund brings the 26-year-old firm’s assets under management to $90 billion, according to a press release. Alibaba reported its slowest-ever revenue growth for the quarter through December, as its core commerce business in China grew only 7% amid an economic slowdown. Net profit fell 74%, in part because the company wrote down the value of its struggling online entertainment division. E-commerce software provider Fabric on Thursday announced it has raised a $140 million Series C led by SoftBank’s Vision Fund 2. The funding round brings the company’s valuation to $1.5 billion, almost double its previous $850 million valuation when it raised a $100 million Series B last July.  Jack Dorsey’s Block, formerly known as Square, lifted its gross profit 47% to $1.18 billion as its cash app and seller businesses grew solidly. But rising expenses put the company into a loss for the quarter.
